\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So your grandmother came from Piddletrenthide and your father was a very old 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 That's right, old {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Portland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} family. Right back a hundred year right back, yes, more - more than now, now 'cos I'm up round seventy-five. Or getting on, I shall be seventy-five now next birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So it'd be about four hundred and fifty years you can trace it back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yes. They up - at Somerset House trace it back and all my - here mind, because - these people that I'm talking about, they used to hold the Reeve stick one time. That's the Lord of Manor. They had the Reeve stick for a g
ood many year he did, Bob Rod did. In fact I wanted that Reeve stick but - I gone done out of it when I went to - went up in 1914. A bloke named Attwell, Dicky Dunnett we used to call him, Dick Atwell had it. And what he done with I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 It was in your family up until then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 They had the marks on them didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
That's right. That's right. They couldn't spell nor write then, used to the mark across. Whoever paid - a mark. With a knife.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Your family must have been an im
portant family on the island to have held the Reeve Stick?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Well they come here when they - far as I can make out - Wyndan Pearce, he traced 'em back and as far as I can remember - they come from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}France{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. They come from France in them days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Had your family been connected with the quarries right the way through?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yes. Yes, they had a - they had their own quarry one time. Down at Wakeham. Yes. Oh yes. Down at church Ope where you've got that ramp under - under Bow and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceName}}Arrow
{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname PlaceType}}Castle{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} where the shee
p come down, they tipped all that down with horse and trap to make a quarry, start the quarry up the back of Wakeham there. You know where you go through straight in front - Lano's house there, and there's another small row of houses down in front of the 
wharf - used to go up through there and their quarry was in there, big patch.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 This was another family concern?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Another family concern. Yes, oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Going back to your brothers and sister, Leonards was the oldest? He was born 1898. Olive, 1902. Thomas - did you call him Thomas or George?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Which one you got there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Harold. Harold. Yes, Harold, he's just died here.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Did you call him Harold or Benjamin?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Harold.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 He was born 1900. Olive 1902. Was it Thomas or George?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Thomas. Tom.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 1903. Albert.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Edward. Albert we call him. Albert. Albert.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 1912.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So you were the eldest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yes, yes. I was born 1898. February the ninth, 1898. You can reckon that up if you like. I was born down Wakeham - down Wakeham. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Is that where your mother and father were living at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yes, down at Robert Rod's house, of course the - porch is all plastered over now so - it's the last house - you know where you go up through the - up through the wood path and
 there was half a barn - half a barn what's still there and then a row of houses isn't there. Well - up this side you see a house there with a porch on and then you see another house and there used to be a row with another porch. My aunt Bess lived in tha
t
 house with no porch. And I was born next door in the one with a porch. And if you scrape the whitewash, then you've got a good layer of cement on there, but if you scrape that off there's a stone there - that is marked Robert Rod and Co. Stone Company. I
 don't believe them people was living there though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 That was your grandfather then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Yes, Robert Rod.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
When was this worked? How long ago was that worked, a hundred years ago or was it longer than that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, no, no. About 1906 they finished near enough along there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So they were still working there when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
They were still working it. 'Cos I remember when the lane got filled in from - what they used to call Coombe's quarry, pulled it down and filled the land in for 'em. Opened another quarry and see - and all done by horse and pots then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was it worked out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Oh it was all worked out that was see, they went - they worked their own land out. Which you was quite entitled to do then, never had to ask. I don't s
ee any of these laws now where you should have permission to - to do up your own place or your own house or your own - ask - I reckon that's all bunkum. The house doesn't belong to you, it belongs to other people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Did your father have his own gang then working on his own quarry?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, all the brothers worked together. Brother and fathers worked together.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 It was a real family concern?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Family concern all the time. That's how it was all the - that's how - that's how {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}St Paul{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}'s got built down East Weare just the same, family concern.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Did the stone from your family's quarry go anywhere in particular?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Oh I don't know where it went to. No, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 You don't know any particular building that it went to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Go on a building
, but I'll tell you what. You could see the road where it used to come out over now before they built the new road.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Whereabouts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Look up there, you'll see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 You mean the road where the stone used to come down the hill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 That's right.
 And how do you think they got it down? Well - you know these - drays and on two wheels, like the old Ancient Britons used to pull don't you. The horses - and two wheels and then the - and then the at the wagon, they put one stone on there, one horse in f
ront, one at - perhaps two behind, pulling back. That's how they used to get it down here. And if it come off - took brutal strength with a porter and jack and jack it up again. How big the stone were.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 And they used to hew it up really square?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 O
h had to make 'em square then. Oh yes, yes. Yes, weren't no corners off. When I went in the quarry first if you knocked a corner off, oh God Almighty. Now it don't matter where - blooming great corner knocked off, the middle of 'em, it goes on just the sa
me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was your father's quarry finished when you started?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yes. YES. I started working when I was twelve. As for my - now what do - you wouldn't do it. A lot of people - of boys wouldn't do it. Three shillings a week. That's pick your tools up in We
ston. Sometimes you'd be four and five. You'd walk right out to Bill like where they've got the branch train to now, and down on the water's edge with your tools. Every morning. Some of 'em went to three shillings a week. And believe me when it did blow f
rom the Nor'east and the - wind catch your fingers, oh you couldn't feel 'em. But we got hardened to it. Yes. That's how that come there. That's arthritis in the joints.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 How long did your family work that quarry then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Well we don't know, don't ask me that, don't ask me that, I don't know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 When it finished what happened to the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Well they just worked on one of the different quarries.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was your father sort of head of the quarry gang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, his father was. 'Cos his father die
d on the crane with heart attack. One minute he was up like that, he fell forward and that was that. Gone.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 This was when it was the hand crane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Hand, that's it, hand crane. Oh before steam and electric -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was that before you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, no, no. Well may have been, but I remember - steam -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Do you remember your grandfather dying?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, no, I can't remember none of that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So was your father head of the gang when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 I expect so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was he the oldest brother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
No, it wasn't oldest. No. The one what could spell the most and do the most work with a pen. No, how about you - you in charge, you can - you can write up better than I can. You can reckon up better than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 This was to negotiate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Tha
t's right. And in them days when they went to school - they had to pay tuppence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 This was when your father went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Yes. When he went to school they had to pay tuppence a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Did he go to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Oh he went to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Did the other members of the family go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Some did, some didn't. But - Jim Rod, he went to apprentice for a monumental mason. He done a lot of work up the - up the St George's church, you know where the - over Weston for - stone over Weston.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was he in the quarry originally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
No. No. Jim, he never went to the quarry. He went - he went a - a monumental mason straight away.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 When you started you went down to the Bill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 I went on the Bill when I was only twelve, walked down to the Bi
ll and walked back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Is this what happened when your family's quarry closed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Oh yes, you had to go different places. That was all finished with. My father, he was working over Weston then. And that - them days I used to go over there with a lump 
of bread, get a hot dinner for one - a piece - a piece of steak about that big, fill up a basin, steak and spuds and cabbage. And a blooming great piece of bread. All wrapped up, used to take it over - take it home and put it up nice and warm. Many a day 
I've had to go over there I have.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was that a regular job that you had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Oh that was in between - when I went to school, that was in between, that was in the school time, that - and I - in the dinnertime I mean, was let out of school twelve 
o'clock and - and - go in the school again by half past one. I'd have me own dinner then I'd go over there. Back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Was it just you or was it a job that somebody in the family had to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Oh somebody in the family'd do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Every day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Every - well, nearly every day anyway. 'Course a lump of beef steak then like that only just cost about tuppence. Never used to gets much. You get a tanner's worth of steak you get - oh - blooming great big piece. More than what you get for four or five
 bob now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 So when your father's quarry finished he went to Weston?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
That's right. Now - he went down, what we call - suck thumb. Suck thumb. He went down there first, 'cos he took me when I was a boy he took me down this fair down there. 'Cos I w
anted to, he said, come on, I'll take you down fair, here you are, come on then. He took me across the Windmills right up across - in house and changed and went down the fair. And that was where I seen me first bike down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 How old were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Oh about six. Six or seven year old, just a - just - to know what - what was what.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 You say you saw your first fight, was this on the booths?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
On the booths, and the big Marine on the horse - on the Cavalry horses won't get off. And the fair chap
 knock him off. Knocked him off. Marine got up but wouldn't fight - fight the - he - the gangway like, he was pressed into that and packed it up and then he went down the Vic there for some more beer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 I gather the boxing booth was a very big attractio
n, it's not very much now is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
No. No. Boxing ring, well blimey - I - I tell you about - oh just coming - just going to start work and another chap was - down with the paint pot by me, see, going along with a - we stopped this 'ere one fair day, we
 was looking at the boxing booths see. So Mac Bowson, he said, I shouldn't mind going in there. I said, go on then, get five bob then. Went in, of course - a fair bloke of fists and that pulled Mac all around the room - and all around the bottom and when 
he come out he said, here, he said, well that's your bloody fault, he blamed me for it. YES? HE said, your bloody fault, he said, like.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 He didn't win his money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 OH he had the money. YES? He had five bob.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 He won it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 No, he didn't win i
t, the bloke give him five bob for having the guts to go in there. He said, you're the first one, he said, you've got more guts than any of 'em. Of course he never hit hard, but he hit him pretty hard enough though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 What was the prize money in fact?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
A pound. That was all. Of course - lot of money in them days you know, a pound was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 Do you remember ever seeing anybody do it when you were younger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid6058468 LR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
No. No. Nobody ever knocked them there people out. They always had something - they say, hey, look over the back, bump. They had a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2562708 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid7431414\charrsid29954 
Yet the quarrymen were pretty strong weren't they, with the hard physical labour?
